Time to Get a CLUE

Text

When you click into a text tile in your workspace, a tray with icons for editing options appears below it. Hover your mouse over the items in the tray for more information (and a keyboard shortcut) about each. Go ahead and make a text tile now, and write down what you're most looking forward to learning in this class. Be sure to try some formatting and list options.

Data and Graphs

Data is the name of the game here, and you'll put your data into tables and data cards, then graph it or calculate with it. You can graph data by choosing the "Graph It!" button from a data set, or you can add data to an existing graph using the Add Data button. You can even create data directly on a graph by plotting points.

Sketch

Sketches are useful for communicating ideas or for documenting parts of solutions. There are lots of tools for letting you make shapes, change colors, group and order things and control the visibility of things. Make sure to open the View/Sort panel on the left of the sketch tile to see what it does. Sketches also let you upload images, which is a good way to show how data was measured and document the way the measurement was taken.

Annotation Arrows (SPArrows)

There's a special feature in CLUE that lets you show relationships between objects either in your tiles or across them. These arrows are made using the blue comment arrow bubble at the top of your workspace. Then you can click on any two end points and talk about the relationship between them.
In this case, we can see the forest for the trees.
